<comment datatype='string'>In the commensal cellulose-producing &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt; strain 1094, BcsQ is required for cellulose production and localizes to the cell poles [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19400787&quot;&gt;Le09a&lt;/a&gt;].  
&lt;p&gt;
In &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt; K-12 strains such as W3110 and MG1655, a &quot;domesticating SNP&quot; consists of a point mutation that introduces a stop codon after the first 5 amino acids of the wild-type &lt;i&gt;bcsQ&lt;/i&gt; ORF.  Additionally, the domesticating SNP lowers expression of both &lt;i&gt;bcsQ&lt;/i&gt; and the downstream &lt;i&gt;bcsA&lt;/i&gt; gene.  After repairing the SNP, the resulting &quot;de-domesticated&quot; W3110 derivative produces cellulose and has dramatically altered biofilm morphology.  A &amp;Delta;&lt;i&gt;bcsQ&lt;/i&gt; mutation introduced into this strain leads to loss of cellulose biosynthesis [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24097954&quot;&gt;Serra13&lt;/a&gt;] (see also [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31604608&quot;&gt;Acheson19&lt;/a&gt;]). 
&lt;p&gt;
BcsQ belongs to the ParA family of ATPases which also includes MinD.  The N-terminal predicted ATP-binding domain of BcsQ (in strain 1094) is required for function, but not for the polar localization of the protein, while the C-terminal domain contributes to both localization and function in cellulose biosynthesis [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19400787&quot;&gt;Le09a&lt;/a&gt;]. In the cellulose producing strain &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt; 1094, the inner membrane and cytosolic Bcs proteins - BcsA, BcsB, BscQ, BcsG, BcsE, BcsR and BcsF - organize in a multisubunit, stable macrocomplex; two-hybrid assays identified multiple direct interactions between the subunits and a low resolution structure has been obtained [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29234007&quot;&gt;Krasteva17&lt;/a&gt;] (see also [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/33712813&quot;&gt;Acheson21&lt;/a&gt;]). 
&lt;p&gt;
A &lt;i&gt;bcsQ&lt;/i&gt; mutant was seen to exhibit filamentous morphology, heterogeneous cell size, and a defect in chromosome partitioning [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12382054&quot;&gt;Kim02b&lt;/a&gt;], but [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19400787&quot;&gt;Le09a&lt;/a&gt;] was unable to reproduce these phenotypes.
&lt;p&gt;
BcsQ: &quot;&lt;b&gt;b&lt;/b&gt;acterial &lt;b&gt;c&lt;/b&gt;ellulose &lt;b&gt;s&lt;/b&gt;ynthesis&quot;
&lt;p&gt;
Related review: [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26077867&quot;&gt;Romling15&lt;/a&gt;]</comment>
